Problem Statement¶

Businesses in the US require competent and skilled staff in order to remain competitive. Businesses frequently use both domestic and international labor to satisfy this demand.

Foreign workers are permitted to enter the United States for either temporary or permanent employment under the Immigration and Nationality Act (INA). Employers must adhere to strict rules when hiring foreign labor in order to protect American workers. The Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC) oversees these regulations.

OFLC reviews employer applications for foreign workers and approves them only if there are not enough U.S. workers available for the job, and if the offered wages meet required standards.

Objective¶

In 2016, OFLC processed nearly 776,000 employer applications for about 1.7 million job positions—a 9% increase from the previous year. As the number of applications grows every year, manually reviewing each case is becoming very difficult.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. As a data scientist at EasyVisa the task is to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  1. Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  2. Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Dictionary¶

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent of the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full-Time Position; N = Part-Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

# removal of outliers

def remove_outliers(df, column, threshold):
  outliers = df[df[column] <= threshold]

  sns.boxplot(outliers[column])       # Plotting box plot
  plt.title("Boxplot without Outliers")
  plt.show()
  return outliers

# columns to check outliers and their respective threshold
columns = ['no_of_employees', 'yr_of_estab', 'prevailing_wage']
threshold = [150, 7, 500]

# outlier removal
no_outliers = remove_outliers(df, columns, threshold)

Observation:

The no_of_employees, yr_of_estab, prevailing_wage does not have outliers.

In [111]:
# feature Engineering

# creating binary flag for full-time position (Y=1, N=0)
if 'full_time_position' in df.columns:
  df['full_time_flag'] = df['full_time_position'].map({'Y': 1, 'N': 0})

# creating feature for difference between prevailing wage and its mean
if 'prevailing_wage' in df.columns and 'prevailing_wage':
  df['wage_diff'] = df['prevailing_wage'] - df['prevailing_wage'].mean()

# creating feature for difference between number of employees and its mean
if 'no_of_employees' in df.columns:
  df['emp_diff'] = df['no_of_employees'] - df['no_of_employees'].mean()

# creating feature for difference between year of establishment and its mean
if 'yr_of_estab' in df.columns:
  df['estab_diff'] = df['yr_of_estab'] - df['yr_of_estab'].mean()

# identifying categorical columns for encoding
cat_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns.tolist()
le = LabelEncoder()     # applying label encoding to categorical variables
for col in cat_cols:
  df[col] = le.fit_transform(df[col].astype(str))

if 'full_time_flag'in df.columns and 'wage_diff' in df.columns:
  df['high_wage_fulltime'] = np.where((df['full_time_flag']==1) & (df['wage_diff']>0),1,0)

In [112]:
# data preparation

# defining features and targets
X = df.drop(columns=["case_status"])
y = df["case_status"]

X = pd.get_dummies(X, drop_first=True)    # creating dummy variables

# splitting the dataset into train and test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X,    # specifying independent variables
    y,    # specifying dependent variables
    test_size=0.2,    # specifying the size of the test set
    stratify = y,   # ensures that training and test set have similar distribution of response variable
    random_state=42)    # specifying the seed value to enable reproducible results

Observation:

  • The target variable is the case_statuus and other columns are the features.
  • The dataset is split into traning and test set with a ratio of 80:20 and it ensures reproductibility of results at a random_state of 42.

Actionable Insights & Recommendations¶

Model Performance Comparision¶

  • Based on the observations of original, oversampled, undersampled and tuned models:
    • Decision Tree:
      • It has an accuracy of approx. 68-71%.
      • The certified case (class 1) has weak generalization in the decision tree classifier.
    • Random Forest and Bagging:
      • It has given the best model across all the sampling strategies with an accuracy of about 78%.
      • The precision and recall are balanced and hence the prediction of certified and denied cases are reliable.
      • Random Forest has also achieved best performance with strong F1 score after tuning the model.
    • AdaBoost and Gradient Boosting:
      • The certified cases are detected well here due to the high recall value.
      • It has a lower accuracy when compare to random forest and bagging.
  • Thus, Random Forest achieves the highest accuracy, and has a balanced recall and precision and is much reliable for real-world use.

Key Takeaways for the Business¶

  • The oversampling and undersampling of models have significantly improved the recall for the certified cases and thus it makes efficient use in business as it is better to validate the models using the balanced datasets before deployment.
  • Ensemble methods like random forest and bagging perform better than single learners like decision tree.
  • The company can acchieve higher accuraccy of 78% using the random forest and hence ensure that applicants are not declined unfairly.
  • Incorporation of advanced techniques like resampling, class weighting and human review for borderline cases will ensure balanced and fair decision making.
  • Limited ability to find the certified cases (recall of 0.50) suggests improvements are required to better capture skilled applicants.

Conclusion¶

  • Most of the company establishments emerged after 1950 with rapid growth after 1990, indicating rapid business expansion. Also 90% of the roles were full-time with majority in West and Northeast regions.
  • Yearly wage jobs are higher than that of hourly and weekly wage jobs.
  • Ensemble methods have outperformed the other models with Tuned Random Forest providing an accuraccy of 78%.
  • The importance of handling data imbalance is understood via oversampling and undersampling the data for the certified cases.
  • The certified and denied cases are fairly consistent across continent, showing location is not a major impact on the case status.

Business Recommendations¶

  • Since yearly wage roles have high certfied rates, businesses should promote annual salary packages rather than hourly or weekly par.
  • This predictive model can be used for the visa application evaluations to reduce manual effort and ensure data-driven decisions.
  • The recruitment in the West and Northeast regions must be increased and the other regions should be explored for better recruitment.
  • Introducing the additional applicant features like skills, experience and past records can further improve the prediction quality.
  • The use of such predictive models ensure better treatment of genuine approvals, improving applicant satisfaction and also maintains control over fraudulent cases.
